Server-Side Includes (SSI) can be extremely dangerous when misconfigured or enabled unnecessarily. SSI allows embedding dynamic content into web pages, but if user input flows into SSI-processed pages, attackers can execute arbitrary commands on your server.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```java
import javax.servlet.*;
import javax.servlet.http.*;
import java.io.*;

public class DynamicContentServlet extends HttpServlet {

    @Override
    protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response)
            throws ServletException, IOException {

        String username = request.getParameter("username");
        String template = request.getParameter("template");

        // VULNERABLE: User input directly embedded in SSI-processed content
        response.setContentType("text/html");
        PrintWriter out = response.getWriter();

        // This content will be processed by SSI servlet
        out.println("<html><body>");
        out.println("<h1>Welcome, " + username + "</h1>");

        // DANGEROUS: SSI directive inclusion with user input
        out.println("<!--#include virtual=\"" + template + "\" -->");
        out.println("<!--#echo var=\"DATE_LOCAL\" -->");
        out.println("</body></html>");
    }
}
```

